\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx360\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 \tab 
Greetings. My name is Iron_Forge, and I have been working on and off with Halo map files of one type or another for a little over a year now. I have remained active in all areas of map formatting of Halo 1 for the xbox as well as the pc. Odds are if you 
have used an application for Halo 1, I have had a hand in it, or the information that led to its conception.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab I have been working on the Halo 2 map format since its release, and this document serves as a collection of the information I have compiled with the help of good friends MonoxideC and ViperNeo. Applying my experience from Halo 1 an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid8260861 d other projects, I am one of a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  handful of people who could be considered experts on the map file formats. Using this document, I hope to pass this on to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7425002 
\par \tab Many things are not contained within this document, for the simple reason of I did not figure out how they work (the BSP is a good example.) That\rquote s not to say these things are still unknown.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 
 ViperNeo had the BSP information completed the same time we were working on models together, due to the strong similarity between them.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7425002 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 1.2 - GLOSSERY
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par  dword \endash  4 bytes of data (double word)
\par 
\par  word \endash  2 bytes of data
\par 
\par  primary magic \endash  A value used to increase offsets, allowing large areas of data to be moved without modifying the offsets contained within it.
\par 
\par  secondary magic \endash  A value used to increase offsets, allowing large areas of data to be moved without modifying the offsets contained within it, primarily used for meta.
\par 
\par  pure offset \endash  A value which represents an offset in the file that has not been modified in any way
\par 
\par  raw offset \endash  A pure offset whose 2 most significant bits represent the file the offset references
\par 
\par primary magic offset \endash  A pure offset whose value has been increased by the primary magic value
\par 
\par secondary magic offset \endash  A pure offset whose value has been increased by the secondary magic value
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f46\fs24\cf16\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\cf0\insrsid7569251 \page }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7569251 Map Information
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f46\insrsid7569251 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.1 - MAP LAYOUT
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab The Halo 2 map files can be broken up into the following sections: header, sound raw data, model raw data, bsp model raw data, model animation raw }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 data, bsp structure, script references}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 , file names, unicode strings raw data, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 other}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
, texture raw data, object index, index padding, object meta information, and finally the cache where applicable.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.2 - PROCESSING
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab When Halo 2 is loaded, it will create cache files (copying the original files to the hard drive of the xbox). The shared and single player shared map files are exceptions to this rule, most likely to lower the load 
times of the game starting, and each map being processed. If your installation has valid bink video files, these will be played during load times, otherwise a progress text will appear on the screen showing the percentage copied.
\par 
\par \tab All loaded files are signed (see section on encryptomatic signature), and should a loading map fail, the engine will retry the copy twice more before giving a \'93dirty disk\'94 error, or a \'93map failed to load\'94 error, depending on the map.

\par  
\par \tab Upon loading a map, only the required resou
rces are placed in memory. As objects appear on screen, the data for them is streamed from the shared files, replacing the very low copy kept in memory with a much richer and more detailed counterparts. This process allows even multiplayer maps to have ac
cess to several hundred megabytes of information, while remaining within the limitations of the xbox hardware.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.3 - MAP HEADER
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab The map header}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs16\f46\super\insrsid7569251 \chftn {\footnote \ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs16\super\insrsid4135236 \chftn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4135236  Please see Appendix I for the struct definitions.}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
 is 2048 bytes just as previous versions of Halo. The version tag is now 8. The index offset is a pure offset pointing to the index header, followed by the meta start, which when added to the index offset will point to the beginning of the meta area. Map 
origin will define the path (and file) the cache was created from, and as such is only defined in the cache files.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.3.1 - FILE TABLE
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab The file table contains full paths for each object in relative order (first filename is for the first object.) The strings are standard ASCII, with a null termination and no padding is used regardless of where the string terminates.
\par 
\par \tab The file table index contains unsigned integers defining the offset which each string begins, also relative. This allows the file table to be read as a single block of characters, and each object to be issued a pointer to the beginning of its string.

\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.3.2 - ENCRYPTOMATIC SIGNATURE
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab The encryptomatic signature is created by xoring every dword after the header together. It is my belief that this value has the single purpose of validating maps copied correctly, and was not used to \'93thwart\'94 would be modders.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.3.3 \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid15607898 
SCRIPT REFERENCES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7425002 \tab Script references link some object to a specific event.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid4132548 
 The string table defining these references is in the same format as the file table, including an index. They can often be found following dependencies such as effect dependencies. This would link that effect to be triggered by a given event, such as a bu
tton being pressed, or an item being picked up. The reference themselves consist of a pair of words, the first being the index to the string in the table, the second being }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid16272642 
the length of the script reference string}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid4132548 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7425002 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.4 - INDEX HEADER
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab The first value in the index header remains the constant used to calculate magic. The object index offset here is a primary magic offset, and points to the object index.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.4.1 - TAG LIST
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab Directly following the index header is the tag list. This list contains all used tags in the map file, and defines their object hierarchy. Thi
s allows the engine to know for example, that all vehicles are a sub class of the unit class, which is a sub class of the object class. I believe the wildcard tags are used as a way of using the primary tag without its parents, though this is just specula
tion.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.4.2 - OBJECT INDEX
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab The object index is a recursively-constructed collection defining all objects in the map. The objects identifier is defined here, which is used to reference the object from all other areas of the map file. The identifier is com
posed of two short values, each are incremented equally throughout the index. The meta offset is a secondary magic offset which points to the beginning of the objects meta.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 2.4.3 \endash  PRIMARY AND SECONDARY MAGIC
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab 
The magic values are used to allow moving large blocks of data without having to modify the data itself. Using a magic value applied to all offsets, after moving the data x bytes, the magic only needs to be increased or decreased 8 to correct all offsets
, rather than each offset needing re-calculati
on. Primary magic is still calculated by magic constant - (index header offset) + sizeof(index header)). Secondary magic, which is now used instead of primary magic for meta related offsets, is primary magic + sizeof(BSP). Since we cannot obtain the size 
of the BSP object without using secondary magic (it is located in the scenery tag), we use the known offset of the meta start and the secondary magic offset of the first object to calculate this value.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f46\fs24\cf16\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b0\cf0\insrsid7569251 \page }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs28\insrsid7569251 Objects
