e no magic applied to them. However, they can reference the current map file, or the three shared files. To do this, it reserves the two most significant (highest) bits to define the referencing file. These are defined as: 00}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\sub\insrsid7569251 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  being local file, 01}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\sub\insrsid7569251 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  being mainmenu.map, 10}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\sub\insrsid7569251 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  being shared.map, and 11}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\sub\insrsid7569251 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
 being single_player_shared.map.
\par 
\par \tab When referencing a raw offset, one should first determine the file being referenced, remove those two bits from the offset value (and with 0x3FFFFFFF), and then seek to that offse
t in the correct file to find the referenced data. Given the size of the shared files, it is possible that the third most significant bit is also reserved for sharing new downloadable content in the future, but this would just be speculation.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 3.2 - UNICODE STRINGS
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab Unicode strings are built to allow for up to nine languages. The globals object defines where each language block is located, and its related information (size, string count, etc.) as needed. Each unicode string object then contains two shorts 
per language, the first defining the offset (as a string count) in the language block that the unicode object begins, and the second defining how many strings are in the object.
\par 
\par \tab This method allows the multiplayer maps to be identical for every version and region of Halo 2. The engine can simply detect you xbox language settings, and supply the correct string(s) form the language block.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 3.3 - BITMAPS & TEXTURES
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab Bitmap objects are collections of the textures in Halo 2, and their layout is rather straightforward.  Each texture is allowed up to six }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 evels}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261  of detail}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 . Each }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 evel }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 of detail }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 is identical to its predecessors first mipmap. So if the first quality level were 256x256, the following woul}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 
d be 128x128. Each level of detail however}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  still contains its own entire set of mipmaps. I suspect this goes further towards Halo 2\rquote s efficient use of memory management.
\par 
\par \tab Each bitmap object may also contain several images, usually used where options between similar sets of images are needed (such as multiple level ima
ges in the main menu.) These will be represented by the bitm struct reflexive. Each bitmap may be extracted as if it were its own object.
\par 
\par \tab Referencing the source to HME/HMT, we can find the different image formats for the different image objects. In addition to these types, 0x11 and 0x12 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 
are both single channel images (you may extract them as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 A8 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10109261 if using the common DDS)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7502792 , and are}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  used for bump maps, and light maps (respectively.)
\par 
\par \tab Many images are still swizzled (a technique for faster memory copies), and this information may also be referenced from the HME/HMT sources.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 3.4 - SOUNDS
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab Sounds were probably the most enjoyable piece of Halo 2 to work on. They entwine with an \'93ugh!\'94 object named \'93I\rquote ve got a lovely bunch of coconuts\'94
, a song done by the amazing comedic group Monty Python. I cannot help but believe this system was done as an easter egg designed just for me as \'93the curious modder\'94
. To Bungie, I thank you (unless of course this was designed to keep us from removing sounds, in which case I sincerely apologize.)
\par 
\par \tab In each sound meta, there is an index and chunk count that references a block in the fifth reflexive in the coconuts object. This block has another index and chunk count, referencing the sixth reflexive in the coconuts object. These chunks reference 
\'93option\'94 sounds, such as several different sound choices for entering a vehicle.
\par 
\par   Each item in the sixth block contains another index and chunk count, this time referencing the ninth reflexive in the coconuts object. The ninth reflexive contains the size and raw offset for each piece of the sound.
\par 
\par \tab Sounds in Halo 2 are xbox adpcm or WMA, depending on the type byte. The WMA sounds can be assembled completely from the raw data pieces. The xbox adpcm pieces require the header be written.
\par 
\par \tab 
If the type byte is 1, then the sound is an adpcm, mono, and 22050kbps sound file. Type 2 is also adpcm, stereo, and 44100kbps sound file. Type 3 is a WMA sound file. There is more to the sound formatting than this, however this was mare than enough for 
me to extract all the sounds.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp20 \tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 3.5 - MODELS
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab 
Models in Halo 2 use a compressed format based on a bounding box.  This bounding box can be found in the first reflexive of the model meta. Using its constraints for each value relevant to the models, the uncompressed value can be found using the formula
 (((shortValue + 32768) / 65535) * (maxValue \endash  minValue)) + minValue.
\par 
\par \tab The model raw data block now contains a header, footer, and several resource chunks. The header contains information regarding how many chunks are in each resource block, allowing you to determine which block contains the information needed}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7502792  (for example, if a given block has 0 chunks, then it will not have a corresponding resource block)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 . The important resource blocks are the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid6698767 mesh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
information block (containing mesh information), the indices block (containing the indices for the triangle strip), the vertices block (containing at minimum 3 shorts defining the x}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7502792 
, y, and z of the vertices),}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  the UV map (containing the compressed UV points.)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7502792 , and the bone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid5191505  map}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7502792 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par 
\par \tab The third dword (as an unsigned integer) in each }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid6698767 mesh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
information block defines how many indices are in that mesh. The indices are placed in order, so each meshes indices can be found after its predecessor in the indices resource block.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid6698767 \tab The vertices are stored with several sized blocks within their resource block}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
, however the x, y, and z points are still represented by the first 3 shorts respectively. The size of each }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid5191505 vertex }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 block can be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid5191505 determined by the type bytes in the model meta}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 . Each short must th
en be decompressed using the above-mentioned formula and their own constraint value, min x and max x for x, and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid10824160 
\par \tab 
If the given vertex type has more than 6 bytes, it is followed by the bone references and weights of this vertex. Both are one byte in length, and the bone references are sorted. Therefore if a bone with a value of 0 is read in any position other than th
e first, this bone reference should be discarded, as should all that follow. Following the bone references are their weights, which are a
lso one byte in length, and can be considered compressed. The weights are a value between 0 an 1 once uncompressed, thus a byte with a weight of 128 will have a weight of 0.5 (or 50% deformation based on this bone.)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f46\insrsid1708009  The exception to this is the 8 byte vertices, where the two bytes following are both bones. If both are set, they each have a weight of 0.5, and if only one is set it is given full weight.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f46\insrsid10824160 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par \tab The UV\rquote s are slightly more complicated. They are compressed in the same fashion as the vertices. However, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid5191505 while }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 UV\rquote 
s must always remain between 0 and 1, their constraints are not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid5191505 governed by the same limits}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 . The resulting uncompressed values can be fixed through \'93
looping\'94 them. If the value is 1.3, the resulting value would be 0.3, and given }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid5191505 the value -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 0.3, the resulting value would be 0.7. The easiest }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid5191505 way to accomplish this is to mod the resulting value by 1, and then if the value is negative, subtract}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251  it from 1.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16589569 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid16589569 \tab 
Since the bones have to act over several different pieces, each raw model block has a bone map, relating the bone byte to the correct bone id. This is a byte array, so if a vertex references bone 0, then boneMap[0] will provide the correct bone id.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\tx180\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid16589569 Back to the meta, t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 he sixth reflexive in the model meta defines the bone hierarchy of the model. When parent, child, or sibling is none, the value will be set to 0xFFFF. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid13507068 
These chunks are the bones which are mapped to from the raw data. The name is a script reference, and defines what the bone is called.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid13507068 
\par \tab The second reflexive defines all the level of det
ails (LOD) for the model pieces. The name is again a script reference defining what this particular LOD is called. This is followed by a reflexive. This reflexive is for all the different options for the particular LOD (for example: base, default, damaged
, etc.) Each of these reflexives consist of another script reference name, defining what this option is referred to as, followed by a series of 5 shorts. These shorts refer to the piece of the model which makes up one of the 5 LODs for this option. The la
st short (following the 5 LODs), defines the piece of the model which has the highest LOD (this should be equal to the 5}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\super\insrsid13507068\charrsid13507068 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid13507068 
 LOD value.) If a model only has 3 LODs, the first three LOD values will be the same, defining one piece to be used for all three levels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid16589569 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 \tab 
The seventh reflexive in the model meta defines a series of locations defining everything from where lights and other effects are located on a model, to where the characters place their hands while using the model.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f46\insrsid13331260  These are set by a script reference to link the point to, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid7569251 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f46\insrsid13331260 and the points location data.
